• At span (3–10) of length 8 we get NT25  
• At span (2–10) of length 9 we then get NT46 via the rule  
    NT46 → NT92 NT25  
  since position 2 is NT92 and (3–10) is NT25.  
• Finally the whole span (1–10) splits at 1: (1–1)=NT29 and (2–10)=NT46, and  
    S → NT29 NT46  

so S ∈ T[1,10].  Therefore the grammar does generate the string.

  NT29 → 't53'                         covers token 1  
  NT46 → NT92 NT25                     must cover tokens 2–18  
  NT92 → 't25'                         covers token 2  
  NT25 → NT22 NT14                     must cover tokens 3–18  
  NT14 → 't56'                         covers token 18  
  NT22 → NT53 NT45                     must cover tokens 3–17  
  NT45 → 't37'                         covers token 17  
  NT53 → NT13 NT55                     must cover tokens 3–16  
  NT13 → 't31'                         covers token 3  
  NT55 → …                            must cover tokens 4–16  

At that last NT55 node, it has just three productions:

  NT55 → NT49 NT91  
  NT55 → 't80'  
  NT55 → 't21'  

Since it must cover 13 tokens (positions 4–16), it cannot use the single‐terminal rules, so it must split via NT49 NT91.  But NT49→NT25 NT87 rigidly forces the NT87 to match one of {t74,t20,t79}.  Checking all possible split points against the actual sequence

    t31, t73, t20, t4, t36, t87, t40, t94, t21, t37, t56, t79, t55

no choice lets NT87 match correctly **and** leaves a valid remainder for NT91.  Hence the derivation gets stuck.  There is no other branching in the grammar that could cover a longer fragment.  Therefore the grammar cannot generate the given string.

    In the grammar, NT46 has only four terminal rules (each yields exactly one token) and exactly one binary rule:
       NT46 → NT92 NT25  
    Since we need 19 tokens from NT46, we must use the binary rule.
